I was surprised that I didn't get a suggestion here

``` rust
fn main() {
    "".is_emtpy();
}
```

From Issue #38166. Some ideas from: https://gcc.gnu.org/gcc-7/changes.html

    const MAX_ITEM: usize = 10;
    fn foo_bar() {}
    fn foo(c: esize) {} // Misspelled type name.
    enum Bar { First, Second }
    fn main() {
        let v = [0u32; MAXITEM]; // Misspelled constant name.
        foobar(); // Misspelled function name.
        let b: Bar = Bar::second; // Misspelled enum variant.
    }

In all four cases I'd like the Rust compiler to suggest the closest names (usize/isize, MAX_ITEM, foo_bar, Bar::Second).

@ConnorGray Now that this has turned into a tracking bug, a good idea would be to pick something more specific and start playing with the code. I usually start with a `git grep` for the error message, and backtrack from there. For example, invalid method calls (like `"".foo()`) always show something like,

    no method named `foo` for type ...

... and the error appears to emit from [here](https://dxr.mozilla.org/rust/rev/ad1461efb92ae85ce8227f52ca79149e368529d1/src/librustc_typeck/check/method/suggest.rs#170), whose caller appears to be [this](https://dxr.mozilla.org/rust/rev/ad1461efb92ae85ce8227f52ca79149e368529d1/src/librustc_typeck/check/mod.rs#2696). The name suggests that it's doing a [lookup](https://manishearth.github.io/rust-internals-docs/rustc_typeck/check/struct.FnCtxt.html#method.lookup_method), which returns a [`MethodError::NoMatch` with some near misses](https://manishearth.github.io/rust-internals-docs/rustc_typeck/check/method/enum.MethodError.html#variant.NoMatch). Perhaps, we could get an alternative from the `NoMatchData`, or if it doesn't exist, we could tweak the function (and probably the struct too?) to get alternative names. Would that be good to get you started? :)

@Wafflespeanut thanks for the nice workflow example. Excuse my ignorance, but what's the significance of tracking vs non-tracking bug? 

I've been working my way down through the code. These are sort of notes for myself, but also can give you an idea of the direction I'm going, in case I'm looking at this wrong. The source for all the method suggestions is a [carried early return](https://dxr.mozilla.org/rust/rev/c0f86f5927377426fbaf72b17c87a6a7291406cb/src/librustc_typeck/check/method/mod.rs#137-138) in lookup_method to [probe_for_name](https://dxr.mozilla.org/rust/rev/c0f86f5927377426fbaf72b17c87a6a7291406cb/src/librustc_typeck/check/method/probe.rs#193-212). probe_for_name looks to be just a helper method which ultimately calls out to [InferContext::probe](https://dxr.mozilla.org/rust/rev/c0f86f5927377426fbaf72b17c87a6a7291406cb/src/librustc/infer/mod.rs#1000-1008). The probe method takes a closure and seems to facilitate the rolling-back of state-changing operations made as part of the name lookup process. [That closure](https://dxr.mozilla.org/rust/rev/c0f86f5927377426fbaf72b17c87a6a7291406cb/src/librustc_typeck/check/method/probe.rs#274-281) creates an instance of ProbeContext, which seems to do most of the heavy lifting. 

@Manishearth, @Wafflespeanut within ProbeContext's methods, there are these "steps" that are referred to (CandidateStep's), and seem to have something to do with type resolution, but I'm having a bit of trouble understanding what they actually are in aggregate. Do you know anything about the overall design, what they represent?

